Another optimization problem that we can solve without Calculus (this
time we'll use Algebra) is the following.


\begin{myexample}[Maximizing Area]
  \label{ex:fixed-perimeter}
  Out of all rectangles with a given fixed perimeter, which one
  encompasses the greatest area?
  
  A reasonable guess is that the correct shape is a square. But a
  guess, no matter how much it feels right, is just a guess. We need a
  convincing demonstration.
  
  To see that this actually is the correct shape, consider a square
  whose side is $s.$ If $s$ is the length of one side then the
  perimeter of our square is (the fixed value) $4s$ and the area is
  $s^2$ (also fixed). Suppose we now increase of two opposite sides
  the length by $x.$ To maintain the same perimeter, we must now
  decrease the width by the same $x.$ The area of this new rectangle
  is $(s-x) \times (s+x)$ is $(s-x)(s+x)=s^2-x^2\lt{}s^2$ but its
  perimeter is still $4s.$
  
  Thus the square has a larger area than this rectangle with the same
  perimeter. Moreover, since we didn't specify a value for $x$ our
  conclusion holds for all possible values of $x$. That is, every
  rectangle with perimeter $4s$ has a smaller area than the square
  with perimeter $4s$.
\end{myexample}

