\section{Fermat's Method of Adequality}
\label{sec:ferm-meth-aedeq}
\markright{\sc{}Fermat's Method of Adequality}

\TLogo{PSP:ferm-meth-find}
\begin{wrapfigure}[15]{l}{2.75in}
  % \vskip-4mm{}
  \captionsetup{labelformat=empty}
  \centerline{\href{https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Fermat/}{\includegraphics*[height=1.65in,width=2.75in]{../Figures/Fermat1}}}
  \label{fig:FermatStamp}
  \caption{\centerline{{Pierre de Fermat}}\\ \centerline{1601-1665}}
\end{wrapfigure}

% \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=1.3in,width=2in]{../Figures/Fermat1}}
% \caption{\centerline{\textcolor{blue}{\href{https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Fermat/}{Pierre
% de Fermat}}}\\ \centerline{\textcolor{blue}{$1601-1665$}}}

In its simplest form an \term{Optimization Problem} can be described
as follows: Given that $y$ depends on $x$, find the value of $x$ that
makes $y$ as large (or as small) as it can possibly be.

For example, if $y=x^2-\frac{29}{21}x+\frac{10}{21}$ then $y$ will be
as small as it can possibly be when $x=\frac{29}{42}$. The question
is, how did we find $x=\frac{29}{42}$?

One of the mathematicians who developed techniques for solving
optimization problems
was
\href{https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Fermat/}{Pierre
  de Fermat} ($1601-1665$) who created what has been called the
\emph{Method of Adequalty}. Fermat's\aside{His name is pronounced
  ``fair mah'', not ``fur mat''.} method was based on the simple
observation that if the maximum value of $y$ occurs when $x$ is equal
to say, $6$, then when $x$ is very near $6$, $y$ will almost be equal
to its maximum value.

\begin{wrapfigure}[14]{r}{3.5in}
  % \vskip-2mm{}
  \captionsetup{labelformat=empty}
  % \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=2.5in,width=4.4in]{../Figures/SantaBarbaraDaylight}}
  \centerline{\includegraphics*[height=2in,width=3.5in]{../Figures/SantaBarbaraDaylight}}
  \label{fig:SantaBarbaraDaylight1}
\end{wrapfigure}
You can see this in the graph at the right\aside{Since there is only
  one number associated with each day of the year this should be a
  discrete graph. Since we'll be more interested in continuous
  functions we connect the dots to create a continuous
  approximation.}.  Notice that the maximum number of daylight hours
(about $14.5$) occurs just after $169$ days (in fact, at day $172$)
and that for several days before or after we have about the same
number of hours of daylight.  This is also true near the minimum which
occurs at day $356.$ Regardless of what the variables represent if the
graph of a function, $f(x)$, is continuous the near a maximum or
minimum: $f(x+h)\approx f(x)$ as long as $h$ is not too big.

Fermat's simple idea was to purposely make the mistake of setting
$f(x+h)$ actually equal\aside{The Latin root \foreign{adaequ\={a}re}
  means to equalize.  When something is adequate, then it is equal to
  the need.} to $f(x)$.  He then rearranged the formulas algebraically
and at the crucial point he would set $h=0$ to ``make it correct.''
An example will make this clearer.

\pagebreak[4]

\begin{myexample}
  \label{example:SquareMinimalPerimeter}
  % \vskip-.3in{}
  \begin{wrapfigure}[5]{r}{1.6in}
    \vskip-5mm{} \captionsetup{labelformat=empty}
    \includegraphics*[height=.8in,width=1.6in]{../Figures/GenericRectangle}
    % \caption{test}
    \label{fig:GenericRectangle}
  \end{wrapfigure}
  In Example~\ref{ex:fixed-perimeter}, we showed that out of all
  rectangles with a fixed perimeter, the one with the largest area is
  a square. Next we will use Fermat's Method of Adequality to examine
  the related question: Out of all rectangles with a fixed area, does
  a square have the smallest perimeter?
  
  Consider a rectangle whose length is given by $x$ and width is given
  by $y.$ The area of the rectangle is given by $A=xy$ and the
  perimeter is given by $P=2x+2y.$
  
  The problem is to minimize $P$ while holding $A$ constant. More
  precisely, our objective is to minimize the function $P=2x+2y$,
  subject to the constraint that the area, $A=xy$, is fixed. First, we
  will use our constraint $A=xy$ to eliminate one of the variables and
  substitute into $P$. Solving for $y,$ we get $y=A/x.$ Then,
  $$
  P=P(x) = 2x+\frac{2A}{x}.
  $$
  We have used function notation for $P(x)$ to emphasize that $P$ is a
  function of $x$ alone.  (Remember that $A$ is constant or
  ``fixed.'')
  
  Fermat's method says to first set
  $$
  P(x+h)=P(x).
  $$
  This gives:
  \begin{align}
    2(\textcolor{red}{x}+h)+\frac{2A}{x+h}=2\textcolor{red}{x}+\frac{2A}{x}.\label{equation:FermAd1}\\
    \intertext{  Rearranging a bit, we get}
    \nonumber
    \textcolor{red}{2x}+\textcolor{blue}{2}h+\frac{\textcolor{blue}{2}A}{x+h}&=\textcolor{red}{2x}+\frac{\textcolor{blue}{2}A}{x}
    \\
    \intertext{so that}
    \nonumber h&=\frac{A}{x}-\frac{A}{x+h}. \\
    \intertext{Adding the fractions gives}
    h&=\frac{A(x+h)-Ax}{x(x+h)}=\frac{Ah}{x(x+h)}. \label{equation:FermAd6}\\
    \intertext{Finally, and crucially, dividing both sides   by $h,$ gives}   
    1&=\frac{A}{x(x+h)}.\label{equation:FermAd7}
  \end{align}
  
  Earlier we had made the ``mistake'' of setting $P(x+h)=P(x)$
  (knowing that this is not true). Now we ``make it correct'' by
  setting $h=0$. This gives: $ 1=\frac{A}{x^2}, \text{ or } x^2=A.  $
  Substituting this into $y=\frac{A}{x},$ we get
  $y=\frac{A}{x}=\frac{x^2}{x}=x.$
  
  Thus $P$ is minimum when $y=x,$ which is to say, when the rectangle
  is actually a square. A moment's thought should make it clear that
  there is no maximum value for $P.$
  
  
  Fermat's method is very slick.  However it contains an inherent
  logical flaw.  We begin by setting $P(x+h)$ equal to $P(x)$, even
  though we know we are making an error. This seems like it might be a
  flaw but it really isn't. When we set $P(x+h)=P(x)$ we are asking,
  ``What happens if they are equal?'' The computations leading up to
  equation~(\ref{equation:FermAd7}) are the answer to that question.
  
  But notice that we got from equation~(\ref{equation:FermAd6}) to
  equation~(\ref{equation:FermAd7}) by dividing by $h.$ From
  arithmetic you know that you can only divide by $h$ if $h$ is not
  zero. Fortunately it is clear that $h\ne0$ since the whole point of
  introducing $h$ is for $x+h$ and $x$ to be two different values.
  However, in the final step, after Equation~(\ref{equation:FermAd7}),
  we took $h=0$ to ``make it correct'' but if $h$ is zero then we
  couldn't have divided by $h$. We seem to be chasing our tails. We
  need for $h$ to be equal to zero and not be equal to zero at the
  same time!
  
  This is the logical flaw.
  
  Since we began with the assumption that $h\neq0$ we can't just
  change our minds later. We can't have both $h=0$ and $h\neq0$.
\end{myexample}

Despite this logical flaw, Fermat's technique does seem to produce the
correct answer. So let's explore it and see what happens.

